Like you, I also consider the test&#39;s exception more interesting than 
the follow-up problems in tearDown(). I&#39;ve fixed it (in 
http://wounittest.sf.net) with the following method in my TestCase 
superclass, which inherits from junit.framework.TestCase.


     /**
     * Runs the bare test sequence.
     * This overwrites &lt;code&gt;runBare()&lt;/code&gt; in &lt;code&gt;TestCase&lt;/code&gt; 
such that exceptions in &lt;code&gt;tearDown()&lt;/code&gt;
     * are only shown if the test itself didn&#39;t throw.
     */
     public void runBare() throws Throwable {
         setUp();
         try {
             runTest();
         } catch (Throwable e) {
             try {
                 tearDown();
             } finally {
                 throw e;
             }
         }
         tearDown();
     }


Christian



&gt; If an exception occurs in a test method, it is thrown to the JUnit
&gt; framwork (testXyz() throws Exception).
&gt;
&gt; In the tearDown() method another exception occurs. The result view
&gt; only shows the exception which occurs in tearDown(), not the one
&gt; which occured before in the test method!
&gt;
&gt; If no exception occurs in tearDown(), then the exception of the test
&gt; method appears in the result view.
&gt;
&gt; So the exception is swallowed by the tearDown() method.
&gt;
&gt; How could I prevent it from swallowing? I want that the result view
&gt; shows both exceptions.
